How would you like it if you suddenly had to pay an extra $30 at the pump every time you filled up?  Or how about a $30 raise in your utility bill?  Nobody likes paying too much for something, especially when other people can get it for much cheaper.  But I'm not talking about gas prices or the hydro, no I'm talking about your Cell Phone and how you're being ripped off, and there's not much you can do about it.

<h2>"Fact"</h2>

Let me introduce you to the Canadian Wireless Telecommunications Association or CWTA for short.  The CWTA are a advocacy group fighting on behalf of the wireless communications industry in Canada.  To put it simply, they are a group that fights so Telus, Rogers, and Bell, can keep ripping you off.  Don't be fooled by their misleading "commitment to consumers", the only thing they care about is getting more money from your pocket.

[img src="http://blog.ianspence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/cwts.jpg"]Did you know? Fact: Wireless rates in Canada are typically lower than in the U.S., in some cases up to 40% lower and smartphone monthly plans are actually less expensive in Canada than in the United States[/img]

You'll be seeing this ad in newspapers for the next few months, and while its it partially true, it's incredibly misleading.  If you have ever consumed any form of news regarding Canadian Telecommunications you will have heard of the term "price gouging" and may have wondered what does that mean.  Price Gouging is the act of charging unfair amounts of money for a product due to lack of competition.  Just like the oil companies, Canadian Telecommunications are doing the same if compared to the US comms.

<h2>What about the little guys?</h2>

So what about the little guys like Wind, Moblicity and Public?  They offer very competitive rates that oftentimes match or beat the US carriers, but they lack the service coverage due to the Advance Wireless Service Auction.  They are very small fish in a vast ocean and sadly they will remain that way if nothing is done.  The carriers are in a catch-22 as they don't have a lot of customers due to lack of service, but they lack service because they have such few customers. At the time of writing, Public offers a $30/month plan that has unlimited Text, Talk, and Data on no fixed-term contract, however, Public only has service in Montreal and Ontario with other cities in the roaming zone.

<h2>Spectrum Management and Auction</h2>

Each carrier in Canada has it's own frequency of the Advance Wireless Service spectrum, and because there is a finite number of spectrums they are regulated and leased to buyers.  This helps prevent spectrums being squatted, however, it hinders small-time carriers from getting started due to the insane cost of buying these frequencies.  Below is a table showing the cost of purchasing a 10, 20, and 40MHz frequency license in every province and territory.

