As on January 18th 2013, Moblicity has 600,000 subscribers, and was planned to be bought out by Telus, which had a $1.2 billion profit in 2011, however because Moblicity owns a different frequency than Telus, this would give them dominance over the spectrum and would violate the AWS Spectrum agreement.

<h2>Changes to the wireless codes</h2>

On December 2nd, 2013 new rules will be imposed by the CRTC in regards to the Wireless Codes of Conduct.  These changes will allow subscribers to:

<ul><li>Terminate their wireless contracts after two years without cancellation fees, even if they have signed on for a longer term.</li>
<li>Cap extra data charges at $50 a month and international data roaming charges at $100 a month to prevent bill shock.</li>
<li>Have their cellphones unlocked after 90 days, or immediately if they paid for the device in full.</li>
<li>Return their cellphones, within 15 days and specific usage limits, if they are unhappy with their service.</li>
<li>Accept or decline changes to the key terms of a fixed-term contract (i.e., two-year), and receive a contract that is easy to read and understand.</li></ul>

However the CRTC did not place any enforcement on price hikes due to the change in regulations, and it's extremely possible that the big three will raise their prices.  Because the change in rules don't apply to current customers, only new ones, the big three are pushing with promotional plans to get more customers locked into a three year contract.

<h2>What can be done?</h2>

As of right now, there isn't much you can do to help end the unfair price gouging.  If you live in a city consider switching to a smaller carrier like Wind, Mobility, or Public.  You'll save plenty and help get them out of their catch-22.  However, switching to a smaller carrier alone won't solve this problem, as I believe the federal government needs to make it's rules regarding price gouging much stricter, giving Canadians much more freedom when choosing a wireless carrier and phone plan.  What ways can you think of that will help?  Let me know in the comments.
